s is a=1, b=0. Term (~a | b).\n         Let's try again. 0s: 0,1,4,5,6,9,10,13,14. X: 3,8,11,12.\n         Group 1: {0, 1, 4, 5} (a=0, c=0) -> (a | c)\n         Group 2: {1, 5, 9, 13} (c=0, d=1) -> (c | ~d)\n         Group 3: {14, 10, 6, 2}? No. \n         Group 3: {14, 10, 6, 4}? No. \n         Group 3: {6, 14, 4, 12}? (b=1, d=0) -> (~b | d)\n         Wait, {6, 14, 10, 2}? No. \n         Let's look at the remaining 0s: 6, 10, 14. \n         6 is 0110. 10 is 1010. 14 is 1110. \n         Can we group {6, 14} with {4, 12}? Yes. (b=1, d=0) -> (~b | d).\n         Can we group {10, 14} with {8, 12}? Yes. (a=1, d=0) -> (~a | d).\n         Remaining 0s: 6, 10, 14. \n         Is 6 covered? Yes, by (~b | d). \n         Is 10 covered? Yes, by (~a | d). \n         Is 14 covered? Yes, by both. \n         Is 9 covered? 9 is 1001. It's covered by (c | ~d) (since c=0, d=1). \n         Is 13 covered? 13 is 1101. It's covered by (c | ~d) (since c=0, d=1). \n         Is 0, 1, 4, 5 covered? Yes, by (a | c).\n         Wait, check 0: a=0, c=0. Correct. 1: a=0, c=0. Correct. 4: a=0, c=0. Correct. 5: a=0, c=0. Correct. \n         Check 6: b=1, d=0. Correct. \n         Check 14: b=1, d=0. Correct. \n         Check 10: a=1, d=0. Correct. \n         Check 9: c=0, d=1. Correct. \n         Check 13: c=0, d=1. Correct. \n         Final POS: (a | c) & (c | ~d) & (~b | d) & (~a | d).\n         Wait, is that minimal? \n         Let's re-verify the 0s again: 0, 1, 4, 5, 6, 9, 10, 13, 14. \n         (a | c) covers {0, 1, 4, 5}. \n         (c | ~d) covers {1, 5, 9, 13}. \n         (~b | d) covers {4, 6, 12, 14}. \n         (~a | d) covers {8, 10, 12, 14}. \n         All 0s: 0(a|c), 1(a|c/c|~d), 4(a|c/~b|d), 5(a|c/c|~d), 6(~b|d), 9(c|~d), 10(~a|d), 13(c|~d), 14(~b|d/~a|d). \n         All 0s are covered. \n         Let's check 1s: 2, 7, 15. \n         2: a=0, b=0, c=1, d=0. \n            (a|c)=1, (c|~d)=1, (~b|d)=1, (~a|d)=0. Wait, (0|1)&(1|1)&(1|0)&(1|0) = 1&1&1&1 = 1? No, POS result should be 0 for 2